## Lesson 45-5: Question 10 (Vocabulary in Context)

### Before "This question asks":
{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}

### Before the h3 heading:
{{+**Question Type:** Vocabulary in Context -- Even if you know the word's dictionary definition, find contextual clues in surrounding sentences. Parallel constructions (where the author uses a similar word in a nearby, structurally equivalent sentence) are the strongest clue.+}}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The parallel construction technique used here -- 'peevish' in paragraph 1 parallels 'sourest' in paragraph 2 -- is an excellent transferable skill for vocabulary-in-context questions. Consider adding a callout flagging this as a reusable technique.", "variant": "comment" }

### After the breakdown table:
{{+**Transferable Skill:** When tackling vocabulary-in-context questions, look for parallel constructions. If the author uses a similar structure in a nearby sentence with a different but equivalent word, that equivalent word is your best clue to the meaning. Here, "peevish" (paragraph 1) and "sourest" (paragraph 2) appear in parallel positions, confirming they are near-synonyms.+}}

